[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD involves use of a domain-specific language (DSL) using natural-language constructs (e.g., English-like sentences) that can express the behavior and the expected outcomes.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD encourages collaboration among developers, quality assurance experts, and customer representatives in a software project.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] It encourages teams to use conversation and concrete examples to formalize a shared understanding of how the application should behave.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD is considered an effective practice especially when the *problem space* is complex.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] A common misconception regarding BDD is that it supposedly is a refinement of test-driven development (TDD).
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] While it was originally derived from TDD practices, the sole purpose of BDD is to gain a *shared understanding* of the problem space and find a way to write this down in a Business Language, using Real data, whilst being Intention revealing, Essential and Focused (BRIEF).
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD combines the techniques of TDD with ideas from domain-driven design and object-oriented analysis and design to provide software development and management teams with shared tools and a shared process to collaborate on software development.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] At a high level, BDD is an idea about how software development should be managed by both business interests and technical insight.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Its *practice* involves use of specialized tools.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Some tools specifically for BDD can be used for TDD.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The tools automate the ubiquitous language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD is a process by which DSL structured natural-language statements are converted into executable tests.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The result is executable specification eventually forming Living Documentation: Requirements that are also the first acceptance tests that drive your software development (Acceptance test-driven development).
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Starting from this point, many people developed BDD frameworks over a period of years, finally framing it in terms of a communication and collaboration framework for developers, QA and non-technical or business participants in a software project.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that software tests should be named in terms of desired *behavior*.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Borrowing from agile software development the "desired behavior" in this case consists of the requirements set by the business — that is, the desired behavior that has business value for whatever entity commissioned the software unit under construction.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Within BDD practice, this is referred to as BDD being an "outside-in" activity.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] TDD does not differentiate tests in terms of high-level software requirements, low-level technical details or anything in between.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] One way of looking at BDD therefore, is that it is an evolution of TDD which makes more specific choices.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Another BDD suggestion relates to *how* the desired behavior should be specified.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests using a semi-formal format for behavioral specification which is borrowed from user story specifications from the field of object-oriented analysis and design.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The scenario aspect of this format may be regarded as an application of Hoare logic to behavioral specification of software using the domain-specific language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that business analysts and software developers should collaborate in this area and should specify behavior in terms of user stories, which are each explicitly documented.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD does not require how this information is formatted, but it does suggest that a team should decide on a relatively simple, standardized format with the above elements.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] It also suggests that the scenarios should be phrased declaratively rather than imperatively — in the business language, with no reference to elements of the UI through which the interactions take place.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This format is referred to in Cucumber as the Gherkin language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD borrows the concept of the *ubiquitous language* from domain driven design.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] A ubiquitous language is a (semi-)formal language that is shared by all members of a software development team — both software developers and non-technical personnel.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The language in question is both used and developed by all team members as a common means of discussing the domain of the software in question.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] In this way BDD becomes a vehicle for communication between all the different roles in a software project.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] A common risk with software development includes communication breakdowns between Developers and Business Stakeholders.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD uses the specification of desired behavior as a ubiquitous language for the project Team members.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This is the reason that BDD insists on a semi-formal language for behavioral specification: some formality is a requirement for being a ubiquitous language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] In addition, having such a ubiquitous language creates a domain model of specifications, so that specifications may be reasoned about formally.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This model is also the basis for the different BDD-supporting software tools that are available.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The example given above establishes a user story for a software system under development.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This user story identifies a stakeholder, a business effect and a business value.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] It also describes several scenarios, each with a precondition, trigger and expected outcome.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Each of these parts is exactly identified by the more formal part of the language (the term **Given** might be considered a keyword, for example) and may therefore be processed in some way by a tool that understands the formal parts of the ubiquitous language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Most BDD applications use text-based DSLs and specification approaches.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] However, graphical modeling of integration scenarios has also been applied successfully in practice, e.g., for testing purposes.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Much like TDD, BDD may involve using specialized tooling.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] BDD requires not only test code as does TDD, but also a document that describes behavior in a more human-readable language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This requires a two-step process for executing the tests, reading and parsing the descriptions, and reading the test code and finding the corresponding test implementation to execute.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] This process makes BDD more laborious for developers.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Proponents suggest that due to its human-readable nature the value of those documents extends to a relatively non-technical audience, and can hence serve as a communication means for describing requirements ("features").
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] In principle, a BDD support tool is a testing framework for software, much like the tools that support TDD.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] However, where TDD tools tend to be quite free-format in what is allowed for specifying tests, BDD tools are linked to the definition of the ubiquitous language.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The ubiquitous language allows business analysts to document behavioral requirements in a way that will also be understood by developers.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The principle of BDD support tooling is to make these same requirements documents directly executable as a collection of tests.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] If this cannot be achieved because of reasons related to the technical tool that enables the execution of the specifications, then either the style of writing the behavioral requirements must be altered or the tool must be changed.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] A separate subcategory of behavior-driven development is formed by tools that use specifications as an input language rather than user stories.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Specification tools don't use user stories as an input format for test scenarios but rather use functional specifications for units that are being tested.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] These specifications often have a more technical nature than user stories and are usually less convenient for communication with business personnel than are user stories.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Such a specification may exactly specify the behavior of the component being tested, but is less meaningful to a business user.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] As a result, specification-based testing is seen in BDD practice as a complement to story-based testing and operates at a lower level.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] Specification testing is often seen as a replacement for free-format unit testing.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The "three amigos", also referred to as a "Specification Workshop", is a meeting where the product owner discusses the requirement in the form of specification by example with different stakeholders like the QA and development team.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The key goal for this discussion is to trigger conversation and identify any missing specifications.
[src:testng/behavior-driven-development] The discussion also gives a platform for QA, development team and product owner to converge and hear out each other's perspective to enrich the requirement and also make sure if they are building the right product.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:testng/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:testng/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:testng/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:testng/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] This is a list of notable test automation frameworks commonly used for unit testing.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] Such frameworks are not limited to unit-level testing; they can be used for integration and system level testing.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] For unit testing, a framework must be the same language as the source code under test, and therefore, grouping frameworks by language is valuable.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] For example, .NET groups frameworks that work for any language supported for .NET, and HTTP groups frameworks that test an HTTP server regardless of the implementation language on the server.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] The columns in the tables below are described here.
[src:testng/list-of-unit-testing-frameworks-p01] Some columns do not apply to some groupings and are therefore omitted from that groupings table.
